<item>
 <title>Gene trees</title>
 <link>https://legacy.vectorbase.org/content/gene-trees-0</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; property=&quot;content:encoded&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;Gene trees in VectorBase are inferred from protein alignments, using the &lt;a href=&quot;/info/genome/compara/homology_method.html&quot;&gt;methodology&lt;/a&gt; developed by Ensembl. From these gene trees (which are reconciled with the species tree as part of the inference) lists of orthologs and paralogs are generated.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All &lt;a href=&quot;/genomes&quot;&gt;VectorBase species with gene sets&lt;/a&gt;, plus &lt;em&gt;Drosophila melanogaster&lt;/em&gt;, are included in the inference of gene trees. In cases where we have more than one &lt;a href=&quot;https://legacy.vectorbase.org/glossary#Assembly&quot; title=&quot;When the genome or transcriptome of a species is sequenced, typically many short random fragments are sequenced and reassembled by a computer algorithm into longer contiguous sequences called contigs. Genomic contigs may be assembled into longer sequences called scaffolds and sometimes, if the depth of sequencing is high enough, there may be enough information to assemble most of the scaffolds into chromosomes.&quot; class=&quot;lexicon-term&quot;&gt;assembly&lt;/a&gt; for a species, only the genes from the reference assembly are used.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Data Access&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interactive versions of the gene trees are viewable in the &lt;a href=&quot;/species.html&quot;&gt;genome browser&lt;/a&gt;, and are also available for &lt;a href=&quot;/faqs/downloads-comparative-data&quot;&gt;download in bulk&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
 <pubDate>Mon, 01 Dec 2014 16:55:17 +0000</pubDate>
 <dc:creator>lawson</dc:creator>
 <guid isPermaLink="false">9768287 at https://legacy.vectorbase.org</guid>
